<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATIONAL LEAGUE ROUNDUP; MADDUX ERA FALLS TO 1.71 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The St. Louis Cardinals are already convinced that Greg Maddux will win a 
third consecutive Cy Young Award. 
</P>
<P>
 "If he doesn't win it, I'd like the see the guy who does," Gregg Jefferies 
said after Maddux threw a five-hitter as the Atlanta Braves won, 6-1, to split 
a doubleheader Thursday at St. Louis. "He's obviously the best pitcher in both 
leagues." 
</P>
<P>
 Maddux (13-5) has three consecutive complete games and leads the major leagues 
with eight complete games. He lowered his earned-run average to 1.71 -- more 
than a point lower than any other starter -- and tied Ken Hill of Montreal for 
the league lead in victories. 
</P>
<P>
 Omar Olivares pitched a three-hitter and Jefferies went three for four with 
three runs batted in as the Cardinals won the first game, 6-3. 
</P>
<P>
 The rare six-game series continues with another doubleheader tonight and 
single games Saturday and Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 Maddux struck out eight and walked none. 
</P>
<P>
 The Braves knocked out John Frascatore, making his major league debut, in 3 
1/3 innings. Tony Tarasco hit a run-scoring double and Fred McGriff followed 
with his 26th home run in a three-run first. Javier Lopez hit a three-run home 
run, his 12th, in the fourth. 
</P>
<P>
 Frascatore (0-1), who was called up before the game from triple-A Louisville, 
gave up all six runs and seven hits. He was optioned back to Louisville after 
the game to make room for Tom Urbani, who will start the first game today. 
</P>
<P>
 In the first game, Olivares (2-2) gave up all three hits and three runs in the 
first two innings, and the only Atlanta baserunners in the next five innings 
came on a pair of walks. 
</P>
<P>
 Olivares retired the final 16 batters to win for the first time in eight 
starts. He walked five and struck out two. 
</P>
<P>
 Jefferies had a run-scoring double in the first and RBI singles in the second 
and fourth off John Smoltz (6-10), who worked six innings and gave up six runs 
on 11 hits in his 200th career start. 
</P>
<P>
 "I threw a lot of pitches that were in a bad location," Smoltz said. "Three 
runs should have been enough for me. I'm as frustrated as anyone else." 
</P>
<P>
 Houston 13, Pittsburgh 6 -- Ken Caminiti drove in four runs and Andujar Cedeno 
hit a three-run homer to help Pete Harnisch win his fifth consecutive start as 
the Astros won at Houston. 
</P>
<P>
 Harnisch (7-4) is unbeaten since returning from the 15-day disabled list on 
June 30. He gave up two runs and five hits in seven innings. 
</P>
<P>
 Houston built a 7-0 lead after three innings against Zane Smith (9-8), who 
gave up nine runs and nine hits in 3 2/3 innings. 
</P>
