<HEADLINE>
<P>
IT'S NOT ALWAYS A LEAN ALTERNATIVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG JOHNSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Despite their reputation as a healthier alternative to burgers, "chicken or 
fish won't always help" to reduce fat content in a fast-food meal, Consumer 
Reports states in its August issue. 
</P>
<P>
 The fat and calorie content of chicken varies dramatically depending on how it 
is prepared, the New York-based magazine reported."In fact, the skin and dark 
meat of KFC's Rotisserie Gold chicken helps make it one of the fattiest foods 
we tested." 
</P>
<P>
 Nutritional data provided by restaurant chains shows that chicken served 
without the skin is lower in calories and total fat than that with the skin 
still on. But nutritionists note that skinning chicken before cooking further 
reduces fat content. 
</P>
<P>
 Consumer Reports' new study did not include fast-food meals at El Pollo Loco, 
Boston Chicken or Kenny Rogers Roasters. 
</P>
<P>
 The magazine reported last year that consumers can find poultry products that 
are "especially low in fat." The bottom line, Consumer Reports says, is that 
"if, like most Americans, you prefer the standard foods, you'll probably 
sacrifice nutrition to taste." GREG JOHNSON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Sidebar 
</P>
</TYPE>
